既有言而不敬于朝堂, 则不敬于父者也.[/INST]Ten ancient Chinese poem may be translated as:

In the mountains and valleys, one does not seek for virtue;
But if one is at the court, one must follow the rules of ceremony.

A gentleman is someone who does not show respect for grass;
Though he may be destroyed at the passes, he still does not think of trickery.

A wandering scholar in the open fields is wise;
In ones own home one can see things clearly.

A nobleman is someone at the foot of the mountains;
One may not seek for benevolence, or one may not be able to tell what it is.

If one is studing beside the road, one must not say there is no respect for ceremony in the mountains and woods;
If one has uttered a word without respect on the court, one has shown no respect for one's father.</s>
